abstract: A German excursionist has just completed his tour round the world. abstract: ST. LOUIS, Mo., Dec. 11.--Reports of seismic disturbances along the Pacific slope of Mexico have recently come from Nogales, Arizona. At 5 o'clock Thursday morning earthquake shocks, varying from one to two minutes duration, were felt at San Blas and Topic Sinaloa. At Mazatlan a rumbling noise was followed by a slight shock. Throughout the State of Sonora at nearly every point shocks were felt.

abstract: BRIDGEPORT, Conn., Dec. 23.--Miss Triphenia Bevens, an old resident of Danbury and one of the oldest persons in this State, died in Danbury last night, aged nearly 102 years. She was born April 14, 1786, and had always lined in Danbury. Her husband, Henry Beveils, served in the war of 1812 and took part in several engagements. Mrs. Bevens was a pensioner. She retained all her faculties up to the time of her death.

When the tree fell it struck another large tree, and both fell on the roof of the mill, crushing it in and doing over $1,000 damage to machinery in the mill.

abstract: PITTSBURG, Penn., Dec. 26.--Edward H. Kendricks, one of the oldest telegraph operators in the country, in a fit of despondency jumped from the Sixth-street bridge about 9 o'clock tonight, and was drowned. His health had been bad for several months, and recently he showed signs of insanity, the result of excessive drinking.
